reviewText:
Tiny And Big: Grandpa's Leftovers, is an excellent game. I'm not one for puzzle games, but I had a great deal of fun with this game (mind you I'm only on level 2 at this point).
First the good;
The music is wonderful and using more tracks as collectables makes me what to actually collect them. I personally find the game is rather easy, but the player can easily make it a bit more difficult by slicing apart blocks, then having to figure out the *new* puzzle, which I did quite a few times without meaning too. the game is great at getting the player to actually feel like what he does matters towards the puzzles, and that no one route is correct. The art style is nice, and suits the gameplay well. The tools you get to use are fun, and one can quickly pick out which one of the three is their favourite. It's incredibly easy to pick up too, and begin finding your own solutions.

Now the Bad;
The plot isn't really there, and often I forgot all about it, focusing more on the actual gameplay. Second, your character, Tiny, moves very quickly, and jumps rather far. This makes the game feel somewhat slippy, and is annoying (for the most part I only died cause I was screwing around and fell).

There's not a whole lot to this game if you don't like the actual gameplay, and people who like solid plots will be disappointed. I'm glad I got T&B on sale, or I would not have bought it. It's too short with too little to pay $10 for, and so I do not recommend buying this game full price. However it is worth it to buy it while is on sale for cheap. Overall I rate this game (based on the first 2 levels + tutorial) a 8.5/10. It's good, maybe even great, but lacks story and length.
